{
  "texts": [
    "Advances in long-read sequencing, such as Oxford Nanopore Technologies (ONT) R10 flow cells, V14 chemistry, and improvements in basecalling accuracy, now enable complete and high-quality assembly of bacterial genomes and plasmids using long-reads only (Sereika et al., 2022; Agustinho et al., 2024; Sanderson et al., 2024).",
    "While WGS of isolates is efficient for monitoring AMR, there are several limitations: First, WGS is typically only performed on a limited number of species subjected to official control.",
    "Second, not all bacteria can be isolated, but even when isolation is successful, culturing and selection further restrict the scope of species and resistances that can be investigated.",
    "Finally, only a small fraction of the bacterial population in a sample is isolated and sequenced.",
    "This risks missing important isolates, species, and resistance mechanisms, creating large blind spots."
  ]
}